01:40.000 --> 01:42.000
by the addition of the output.

01:43.000 --> 01:45.000
5 divided by 1 is 5.

01:48.000 --> 01:51.000
Let's move on to the fourth question of our topic.

01:52.000 --> 01:55.000
The costs in the short term.

01:55.000 --> 01:57.000
Let me remind you once again

01:57.000 --> 02:01.000
that the short term in the microeconomics

02:01.000 --> 02:05.000
is the period during which

02:05.000 --> 02:10.000
some factors of production can't be changed,

02:10.000 --> 02:13.000
while others can be changed.

02:14.000 --> 02:18.000
Usually, the capital is considered

02:18.000 --> 02:21.000
the variable factor of production,

02:21.000 --> 02:24.000
and the labor is considered the variable factor.

02:25.000 --> 02:31.000
Accordingly, the costs of capital in the short term

02:31.000 --> 02:33.000
are the constant costs,

02:34.000 --> 02:38.000
and the costs of labor in the short term are the variable costs.

02:41.000 --> 02:47.000
Let's see what the functions of costs in the short term can be.

02:48.000 --> 02:51.000
Let's start with the constant costs.

02:52.000 --> 02:53.000
Look at the slide.

02:55.000 --> 02:56.000
Once again.

02:56.000 --> 03:00.000
The constant costs are the costs

03:00.000 --> 03:05.000
that do not change with the change in the volume of the output.

03:06.000 --> 03:07.000
Look.

03:08.000 --> 03:10.000
The output changes in the left graph,

03:11.000 --> 03:14.000
and the constant costs do not change.

03:14.000 --> 03:18.000
Accordingly, the function of the constant costs

03:18.000 --> 03:22.000
is a straight line parallel to the x-axis.

03:25.000 --> 03:29.000
Now let's talk about the function of the average constant costs.

03:30.000 --> 03:33.000
How are the average constant costs calculated?

03:33.000 --> 03:35.000
We've already talked about it.

03:36.000 --> 03:42.000
They are obtained by dividing the constant costs by the volume of the output.

03:44.000 --> 03:47.000
The constant costs are not changed by the numerator,

03:47.000 --> 03:50.000
but the volume of the output is changed by the denominator.

03:51.000 --> 03:55.000
Well, ask any value of the constant costs.

03:56.000 --> 03:58.000
Let's say 10.

03:59.000 --> 04:01.000
Let the output be equal to 1.

04:02.000 --> 04:04.000
What are the average constant costs?

04:07.000 --> 04:09.000
10 divided by 1 is 10.

04:09.000 --> 04:11.000
Let's say the output is equal to 2.

04:12.000 --> 04:14.000
The constants do not change.

04:14.000 --> 04:16.000
What are the average constants?

04:17.000 --> 04:20.000
10 divided by 2 is 5.

04:21.000 --> 04:23.000
Let the output be equal to 5.

04:24.000 --> 04:28.000
The average constant costs 10 divided by 5 is 2.

04:29.000 --> 04:31.000
Let the output be equal to 10.

04:32.000 --> 04:34.000
10 divided by 10 is 1.

04:34.000 --> 04:36.000
10 divided by 10 is 1.

04:37.000 --> 04:40.000
Let the output be very large.

04:41.000 --> 04:44.000
The average constant costs are 10.

04:45.000 --> 04:48.000
10 to a very large value will be a very small value.

04:49.000 --> 04:51.000
Accordingly, with the increase in the output,

04:51.000 --> 04:54.000
the average constant costs tend to zero.

04:55.000 --> 04:58.000
In general, the function of the average constant costs

04:58.000 --> 05:00.000
is a parable,

05:01.000 --> 05:03.000
hyperbola, excuse me,

05:03.000 --> 05:06.000
which is visible on the right side of the graph.

05:12.000 --> 05:16.000
And how will the functions of other costs change?

05:17.000 --> 05:20.000
Here, the answer cannot be given unambiguously.

05:22.000 --> 05:25.000
Everything will depend on the assumptions.

05:26.000 --> 05:30.000
Let's first consider the simplified functions of costs.

05:31.000 --> 05:33.000
They are based on the assumption

05:34.000 --> 05:37.000
that the maximum costs are constant.

05:39.000 --> 05:42.000
What does it mean that the maximum costs are constant?

05:43.000 --> 05:46.000
This means that with the increase in the output,

05:49.000 --> 05:52.000
the costs are increasing all the time

05:52.000 --> 05:55.000
at the same value.

05:57.000 --> 05:59.000
Let's take an example from trading.

06:01.000 --> 06:03.000
Let there be a store in front of us

06:04.000 --> 06:06.000
that sells, say, beer.

06:08.000 --> 06:11.000
For trading, the volume of the output

06:12.000 --> 06:15.000
is the number of sold goods,

06:16.000 --> 06:18.000
that is, sold bottles of beer.

06:19.000 --> 06:22.000
What are the costs in trading usually?

06:23.000 --> 06:25.000
They are variable.

06:28.000 --> 06:30.000
To sell beer,

06:31.000 --> 06:33.000
you need to buy it from the store.

06:34.000 --> 06:36.000
The more beer we sell,

06:37.000 --> 06:40.000
the more beer we have to buy.

06:41.000 --> 06:44.000
Accordingly, the costs of buying beer

06:44.000 --> 06:47.000
increase with the volume of sales,

06:48.000 --> 06:50.000
that is, with the volume of the output.

06:51.000 --> 06:53.000
Therefore, for trading,

06:54.000 --> 06:56.000
the costs of buying are variable.

06:57.000 --> 07:00.000
All other costs, let's consider them constant.

07:01.000 --> 07:04.000
Those that do not change with the increase in the output.

07:05.000 --> 07:07.000
The rent is not changed,

07:08.000 --> 07:10.000
the electricity is not changed,

07:11.000 --> 07:13.000
the costs of electricity,

07:14.000 --> 07:16.000
even if no one bought anything from us,

07:17.000 --> 07:19.000
the rent must be paid,

07:20.000 --> 07:22.000
the store is open, the refrigerators are working,

07:23.000 --> 07:24.000
the store is lit.

07:25.000 --> 07:27.000
We will also consider the sales salary

07:28.000 --> 07:30.000
independent of the volume of the output,

07:31.000 --> 07:33.000
that is, we will also consider it as a constant cost.

07:34.000 --> 07:36.000
Look at the table.

07:37.000 --> 07:40.000
The output changes from 0 to 100.

07:41.000 --> 07:44.000
That is, the number of sold bottles changes from 0 to 100.

07:45.000 --> 07:48.000
Constant costs I have determined in terms of 100 rubles.

07:49.000 --> 07:52.000
They do not depend on the output.

07:54.000 --> 07:56.000
And variable costs, I repeat,

07:57.000 --> 07:59.000
are the costs of buying beer.

08:00.000 --> 08:07.000
Let's assume that we buy every bottle of beer for 5 rubles.

08:07.000 --> 08:14.000
So, if we did not buy or sell any beer,

08:15.000 --> 08:19.000
the variable costs are 0.

08:20.000 --> 08:23.000
If we bought and sold one bottle of beer,

08:24.000 --> 08:27.000
the variable costs are the costs of buying this bottle,

08:28.000 --> 08:29.000
that is, 5 rubles.

08:30.000 --> 08:32.000
If we bought and sold two bottles of beer,

08:33.000 --> 08:36.000
the variable costs are 10 rubles.

08:37.000 --> 08:38.000
And so on.

08:39.000 --> 08:40.000
15, 20, 25, and so on.

08:41.000 --> 08:46.000
Variable costs are increasing all the time.

08:47.000 --> 08:48.000
How much?

08:49.000 --> 08:53.000
With each next unit of the output for 5 rubles.

08:54.000 --> 08:58.000
These are additional costs or maximum costs.

09:00.000 --> 09:01.000
Look.

09:02.000 --> 09:03.000
The fifth column.

09:04.000 --> 09:06.000
Maximum costs are always 5, 5, 5, 5.

09:07.000 --> 09:09.000
What are the total costs?

09:10.000 --> 09:13.000
With zero output, the variable costs are 0,

09:14.000 --> 09:16.000
but the constant costs still have to be carried.

09:17.000 --> 09:20.000
So, the total costs are constant.

09:21.000 --> 09:22.000
100 rubles.

09:23.000 --> 09:26.000
With one output, the constant costs are 100,

09:27.000 --> 09:29.000
the variable costs are 5, and so on.

09:32.000 --> 09:33.000
According to the well-known formulas,

09:33.000 --> 09:37.000
we can calculate the average constant and average variable costs,

09:38.000 --> 09:40.000
as well as the average total costs.

09:42.000 --> 09:44.000
But here's what I want to draw your attention to.

09:45.000 --> 09:49.000
The maximum costs are constant.

09:50.000 --> 09:53.000
With each next unit of the output,

09:54.000 --> 09:58.000
the maximum costs are increasing all the time

09:59.000 --> 10:01.000
at the same value, at 5 rubles.

10:01.000 --> 10:02.000
But in this case,

10:03.000 --> 10:09.000
they are necessarily equal to the average variable costs.

10:13.000 --> 10:17.000
In fact, if we have an output equal to 1,

10:18.000 --> 10:20.000
the variable costs are 5.

10:21.000 --> 10:24.000
With the output of 2 units, the variable costs are 10.

10:25.000 --> 10:26.000
With 3 units, 15.

10:27.000 --> 10:28.000
With 4, 20.

10:28.000 --> 10:29.000
With 5, 25.

10:30.000 --> 10:34.000
So, the average variable costs are always 5.

10:36.000 --> 10:39.000
The average variable costs, in my conditional example,

10:40.000 --> 10:44.000
are exactly equal to the purchase price of one bottle of beer.

10:48.000 --> 10:50.000
And this is reflected in the following slide.

10:51.000 --> 10:52.000
Look.

10:53.000 --> 10:55.000
We have a figure along the x-axis.

10:55.000 --> 10:56.000
And along the y-axis,

10:57.000 --> 11:00.000
we have the maximum and average variable costs.

11:01.000 --> 11:04.000
The maximum costs remain the same

11:05.000 --> 11:07.000
with the increase in the output.

11:09.000 --> 11:13.000
And they are necessarily equal to the average variable costs.

11:15.000 --> 11:20.000
Now look at how the functions of the variable and the total costs

11:21.000 --> 11:22.000
will work.

11:22.000 --> 11:24.000
I have already talked about the constant costs.

11:25.000 --> 11:26.000
The function of the constant costs

11:27.000 --> 11:29.000
is parallel to the x-axis.

