Let's go back to our table.

11:36.000 --> 11:39.000
Look at how the variable costs change.

11:41.000 --> 11:42.000
With the output of 0, they are 0.

11:43.000 --> 11:44.000
With the output of 1, they are 5.

11:45.000 --> 11:46.000
With the output of 2, they are 5.

11:47.000 --> 11:48.000
With the output of 3, they are 5.

11:49.000 --> 11:50.000
With the output of 4, they are 5.

11:50.000 --> 11:51.000
With the output of 1, they are 5.

11:52.000 --> 11:53.000
With the output of 2, they are 10, and so on.

11:54.000 --> 11:56.000
So the function of the variable costs

11:57.000 --> 11:59.000
is a linear function

12:00.000 --> 12:02.000
coming from the origin of the coordinates.

12:05.000 --> 12:08.000
This is how it is shown in the graph.

12:09.000 --> 12:13.000
And how will the function of the total costs work?

12:16.000 --> 12:17.000
Look.

12:17.000 --> 12:19.000
With the output of 0,

12:20.000 --> 12:22.000
the variable costs, as we have already said,

12:23.000 --> 12:24.000
are 0.

12:25.000 --> 12:28.000
But the constant costs are not 0,

12:29.000 --> 12:30.000
because they must be carried

12:31.000 --> 12:34.000
with any volume of the output.

12:36.000 --> 12:38.000
So with the zero output,

12:39.000 --> 12:42.000
the total costs are constant.

12:43.000 --> 12:46.000
And then the function of the total costs

12:47.000 --> 12:48.000
is a linear function

12:49.000 --> 12:54.000
parallel to the function of the variable costs.

12:56.000 --> 13:01.000
The difference between the total and the variable costs

13:02.000 --> 13:04.000
is the constant costs.

13:05.000 --> 13:06.000
And this value does not change.

13:07.000 --> 13:08.000
Therefore, these two functions

13:09.000 --> 13:10.000
go parallel to each other.

13:12.000 --> 13:13.000
And now let's see

13:13.000 --> 13:17.000
how the functions of the average costs work.

13:21.000 --> 13:22.000
Let's recall the formula.

13:24.000 --> 13:26.000
What are the average and total costs?

13:29.000 --> 13:33.000
These are the average constant costs

13:34.000 --> 13:40.000
plus the average variable costs.

13:43.000 --> 13:47.000
What do we know about the average constant costs?

13:49.000 --> 13:50.000
With the increase in the output,

13:51.000 --> 13:55.000
they decrease and tend to 0.

14:00.000 --> 14:03.000
And what do we know about the average variable costs?

14:04.000 --> 14:07.000
In this model, they do not change,

14:08.000 --> 14:10.000
they are a constant value.

14:13.000 --> 14:17.000
But if this variable decreases and tends to 0,

14:18.000 --> 14:21.000
and the second variable is a constant,

14:23.000 --> 14:26.000
then what does the sum tend to?

14:28.000 --> 14:36.000
The sum tends to the average variable costs.

14:39.000 --> 14:41.000
This is shown in the graph.

14:42.000 --> 14:43.000
Look.

14:44.000 --> 14:46.000
The higher the output,

14:47.000 --> 14:50.000
the lower the average total costs,

14:51.000 --> 14:54.000
which, however, tend not to 0,

14:55.000 --> 14:57.000
but to the average variable costs.

14:59.000 --> 15:04.000
What conclusion can we draw?

15:06.000 --> 15:08.000
The higher the output,

15:09.000 --> 15:16.000
the lower the average constant

15:17.000 --> 15:20.000
and, accordingly, the average total costs.

