23:01.000 --> 23:04.000
aim at the average and total costs.

23:06.000 --> 23:08.000
That's all.

23:09.000 --> 23:11.000
The fourth question of this topic is

23:12.000 --> 23:14.000
the costs in the short term.

23:15.000 --> 23:17.000
There is also the fifth question of the topic.

23:18.000 --> 23:20.000
The costs in the long term.

23:21.000 --> 23:23.000
There is nothing fundamentally new there,

23:24.000 --> 23:26.000
except that I want to emphasize

23:27.000 --> 23:30.000
that in the long term

23:31.000 --> 23:34.000
there are no constant costs.

23:36.000 --> 23:38.000
All costs become variable.

23:39.000 --> 23:40.000
Why?

23:41.000 --> 23:44.000
Because in the long term

23:45.000 --> 23:48.000
the company can change all the production factors.

23:49.000 --> 23:51.000
It can hire additional workers,

23:52.000 --> 23:54.000
it can install additional equipment,

23:55.000 --> 23:59.000
it can rent a more spacious building.

24:00.000 --> 24:03.000
All the production factors become variable,

24:03.000 --> 24:07.000
so all the costs also become variable.

24:08.000 --> 24:13.000
So there is no function of average and constant costs.

24:14.000 --> 24:15.000
But there is one function.

24:16.000 --> 24:18.000
The function of the limit costs

24:19.000 --> 24:21.000
and there is a function of the average costs.

24:22.000 --> 24:23.000
And it will be the same.

24:24.000 --> 24:26.000
The function of the limit costs decreases at first,

24:27.000 --> 24:28.000
then reaches the minimum,

24:29.000 --> 24:30.000
then begins to increase.

24:30.000 --> 24:32.000
The function of the average and constant costs

24:33.000 --> 24:34.000
decreases at first,

24:35.000 --> 24:36.000
then reaches the minimum

24:37.000 --> 24:39.000
at the intersection point

24:40.000 --> 24:42.000
with the function of the limit costs.

24:43.000 --> 24:45.000
After that, the function of the average and constant costs

24:46.000 --> 24:47.000
begins to increase.

24:55.000 --> 24:56.000
Ladies and gentlemen,

24:57.000 --> 24:59.000
we begin the fourth topic of our course.

25:00.000 --> 25:02.000
Market structures.

25:03.000 --> 25:04.000
Company behavior.

25:05.000 --> 25:06.000
Here we will talk about

25:07.000 --> 25:11.000
how the company operates in certain market conditions.

25:12.000 --> 25:14.000
And it is probably obvious

25:15.000 --> 25:16.000
that the behavior of the company

25:17.000 --> 25:21.000
depends not only on the number of resources it has,

25:22.000 --> 25:25.000
but also on the market environment in which it operates.

25:26.000 --> 25:27.000
In other words,

25:27.000 --> 25:31.000
the behavior of the company depends on the type of market.

25:32.000 --> 25:33.000
And now look at the slide, please.

25:34.000 --> 25:37.000
The first question that we will consider

25:38.000 --> 25:40.000
is called the types of market structures.

25:41.000 --> 25:44.000
Or we will talk about the types of markets.

25:46.000 --> 25:47.000
Look, please.

25:48.000 --> 25:50.000
There is a microeconomics that highlights

25:51.000 --> 25:53.000
four types of market structures

25:54.000 --> 25:55.000
or the form of market organization.

25:56.000 --> 25:57.000
These are

25:58.000 --> 25:59.000
perfect competition,

26:00.000 --> 26:01.000
monopoly,

26:02.000 --> 26:03.000
oligopoly,

26:04.000 --> 26:05.000
monopolistic competition.

26:10.000 --> 26:13.000
Let's start with perfect competition.

26:14.000 --> 26:18.000
But very often perfect competition is misunderstood.

26:19.000 --> 26:21.000
They think that perfect competition

26:22.000 --> 26:23.000
is something like

26:26.000 --> 26:29.000
completely cruel, ruthless competition.

26:30.000 --> 26:31.000
In fact, it is nothing like that.

26:32.000 --> 26:33.000
The definition is very simple.

26:34.000 --> 26:35.000
Perfect competition

26:37.000 --> 26:38.000
is a market structure

26:40.000 --> 26:41.000
in which

26:42.000 --> 26:43.000
there are so many

26:44.000 --> 26:45.000
sellers and buyers

26:46.000 --> 26:48.000
that none of them,

26:49.000 --> 26:51.000
changing the volume of their offer

26:52.000 --> 26:53.000
or their demand,

26:53.000 --> 26:57.000
is able to affect the market price.

26:58.000 --> 26:59.000
The price of a product

27:00.000 --> 27:01.000
on a perfectly competitive market

27:02.000 --> 27:04.000
is determined by the interaction

27:05.000 --> 27:07.000
of thousands of independent buyers

27:08.000 --> 27:10.000
and hundreds of independent sellers.

27:11.000 --> 27:13.000
Each buyer and each seller

27:14.000 --> 27:17.000
is a kind of a sand in the scale of the market

27:18.000 --> 27:20.000
that can not change anything in the market

27:20.000 --> 27:22.000
by their behavior.

27:25.000 --> 27:29.000
Let's look at the signs of perfect competition.

27:32.000 --> 27:34.000
I have already told you about the first sign.

27:35.000 --> 27:36.000
Look, here is the sign.

27:37.000 --> 27:39.000
Each of the very large numbers of sellers and buyers

27:40.000 --> 27:42.000
occupies such a small share of the market

27:43.000 --> 27:45.000
that it cannot change the market price

27:46.000 --> 27:47.000
by its behavior,

27:47.000 --> 27:49.000
but can sell or buy

27:50.000 --> 27:52.000
as much of its product

27:53.000 --> 27:55.000
at this price.

27:56.000 --> 27:59.000
Let's take this example.

28:00.000 --> 28:01.000
I will give it to you,

28:02.000 --> 28:03.000
it will probably fit.

28:04.000 --> 28:05.000
Here is a friend

28:06.000 --> 28:08.000
living in the Volgograd province

28:09.000 --> 28:10.000
calling me to Moscow

28:11.000 --> 28:13.000
and asking how much tomatoes are in Moscow.

28:14.000 --> 28:15.000
It was summer

28:15.000 --> 28:16.000
and not last year,

28:17.000 --> 28:19.000
I do not remember what I answered,

28:20.000 --> 28:22.000
well, let's say 10 rubles per kilogram.

28:23.000 --> 28:25.000
She had a curious curiosity.

28:26.000 --> 28:30.000
She was going to bring a truck with Volga tomatoes to Moscow.

28:31.000 --> 28:32.000
So,

28:33.000 --> 28:36.000
what did she get from my information?

28:37.000 --> 28:38.000
The price of tomatoes in Moscow

28:39.000 --> 28:41.000
is 10 rubles per kilogram.

28:41.000 --> 28:43.000
She came from the fact that

28:44.000 --> 28:46.000
if today the price is such,

28:47.000 --> 28:49.000
then its appearance or not

28:50.000 --> 28:51.000
in the market

28:52.000 --> 28:55.000
cannot affect the price in any way.

28:56.000 --> 28:58.000
But on the other hand,

28:59.000 --> 29:00.000
she is sure

29:01.000 --> 29:03.000
that since it occupies a negligible small share

29:04.000 --> 29:05.000
in the tomato market,

29:06.000 --> 29:08.000
it is not profitable

29:08.000 --> 29:10.000
for her to sell any number of tomatoes

29:11.000 --> 29:13.000
at this price of 10 rubles per kilogram.

29:14.000 --> 29:15.000
That is,

29:16.000 --> 29:18.000
a ton, three, even five,

29:19.000 --> 29:21.000
and she just does not have more.

29:22.000 --> 29:24.000
It is clear that if she brought to Moscow

29:25.000 --> 29:26.000
at the same time,

29:27.000 --> 29:29.000
let's say, a thousand tons of tomatoes,

29:30.000 --> 29:31.000
then such a large seller

29:32.000 --> 29:34.000
would definitely affect the price.

29:35.000 --> 29:37.000
But this would already be a problem.

29:38.000 --> 29:40.000
This is not a condition of perfect competition.

29:41.000 --> 29:42.000
I want to emphasize once again

29:43.000 --> 29:45.000
that in the conditions of perfect competition,

29:47.000 --> 29:50.000
the market price is determined by the interaction

29:51.000 --> 29:54.000
of thousands of independent buyers,

29:55.000 --> 29:57.000
hundreds of independent sellers,

29:58.000 --> 30:00.000
each grain in the general market scale,

30:01.000 --> 30:02.000
and no one taken separately

30:03.000 --> 30:04.000
can affect the price.

30:05.000 --> 30:06.000
Yes, another example,

30:06.000 --> 30:08.000
so that it may be better understood.

30:09.000 --> 30:11.000
You ran into a neighbor

30:12.000 --> 30:13.000
at the entrance.

30:14.000 --> 30:15.000
You see that he is walking

30:16.000 --> 30:17.000
from the market.

30:18.000 --> 30:19.000
You ask him,

30:20.000 --> 30:21.000
how much are the tomatoes?

30:22.000 --> 30:24.000
He answers, 10 rubles per kilogram.

30:25.000 --> 30:27.000
So, what do you get out of it?

30:28.000 --> 30:30.000
If the price has risen so fast today,

30:31.000 --> 30:33.000
your appearance or non-appearance

30:33.000 --> 30:35.000
on the market as a buyer

30:36.000 --> 30:38.000
again cannot affect the price.

30:39.000 --> 30:41.000
But you can buy a kilogram,

30:42.000 --> 30:44.000
three, five, even ten rubles

30:45.000 --> 30:47.000
for this price of 10 rubles.

30:48.000 --> 30:49.000
That is, you also feel

30:50.000 --> 30:51.000
like a perfect competitor

30:52.000 --> 30:53.000
on the tomato market,

30:54.000 --> 30:55.000
but not as a seller,

30:56.000 --> 30:57.000
but as a buyer.

30:58.000 --> 31:00.000
Let's look at the graph.

31:00.000 --> 31:02.000
The equilibrium market price

31:03.000 --> 31:04.000
and the demand curve

31:05.000 --> 31:07.000
for the product of a separate company.

31:08.000 --> 31:10.000
Look, two graphs are next to each other.

31:11.000 --> 31:12.000
The left graph illustrates

31:13.000 --> 31:14.000
the demand and supply

31:15.000 --> 31:17.000
on a completely competitive market.

31:18.000 --> 31:19.000
I repeat again,

31:20.000 --> 31:22.000
there are thousands of buyers

31:23.000 --> 31:25.000
and hundreds of independent sellers.

31:26.000 --> 31:27.000
On the x-axis,

31:28.000 --> 31:29.000
we put the price

31:30.000 --> 31:32.000
and the total number of tomatoes

31:33.000 --> 31:35.000
sold and bought on this market.

31:36.000 --> 31:37.000
And what do we see?

31:38.000 --> 31:40.000
That at the price of P with an asterisk,

31:41.000 --> 31:44.000
we observe a kind of market equilibrium.

31:45.000 --> 31:47.000
Demand on the tomato market

31:48.000 --> 31:49.000
by all buyers

31:50.000 --> 31:51.000
is equal to supply on this market

31:52.000 --> 31:53.000
by all sellers.

31:54.000 --> 31:56.000
Now look at the right graph.

31:57.000 --> 31:58.000
You see, on the x-axis

31:58.000 --> 31:59.000
I put, I mean,

32:00.000 --> 32:01.000
the production, volume,

32:02.000 --> 32:04.000
the volume of Kumaloe.

32:05.000 --> 32:07.000
This is a separate company.

32:08.000 --> 32:10.000
This is, figuratively speaking,

32:11.000 --> 32:12.000
my tomato friend.

32:13.000 --> 32:14.000
If on the left graph

32:15.000 --> 32:16.000
the account is at 1000 tons,

32:17.000 --> 32:18.000
then on the right graph

32:19.000 --> 32:20.000
her account is only at tons.

32:21.000 --> 32:23.000
She is a seed in the market scale.

32:24.000 --> 32:25.000
And she accepts

32:25.000 --> 32:27.000
the market price P with an asterisk

32:28.000 --> 32:30.000
as a given price.

32:31.000 --> 32:32.000
As economists say,

32:33.000 --> 32:35.000
she is a price taker.

32:36.000 --> 32:38.000
She accepts this price as a given price

32:39.000 --> 32:41.000
and can sell any number of her tomatoes

32:42.000 --> 32:43.000
at this price.

32:44.000 --> 32:45.000
Please note

32:46.000 --> 32:48.000
that in the conditions of perfect competition

32:49.000 --> 32:50.000
between the two companies,

32:51.000 --> 32:53.000
the price of P with an asterisk

32:53.000 --> 32:55.000
cannot be increased.

32:56.000 --> 32:58.000
No one will buy tomatoes from her.

32:59.000 --> 33:00.000
What's the point

33:01.000 --> 33:02.000
if there are hundreds of sellers

33:03.000 --> 33:04.000
with a lower price?

33:05.000 --> 33:06.000
And it makes no sense

33:07.000 --> 33:08.000
to reduce the price

33:09.000 --> 33:10.000
because at this price

33:11.000 --> 33:12.000
she can sell

33:13.000 --> 33:15.000
any number of her tomatoes.

33:16.000 --> 33:17.000
This is the first sign

33:18.000 --> 33:20.000
of perfect competition.

33:20.000 --> 33:22.000
Let's go back to our signs.

33:23.000 --> 33:25.000
Let's look at the second sign.

33:26.000 --> 33:28.000
The complete uniformity of the product.

33:29.000 --> 33:31.000
The absence of trademarks.

33:32.000 --> 33:34.000
What does this mean?

33:35.000 --> 33:37.000
The product of different sellers

33:38.000 --> 33:40.000
is exactly the same

33:41.000 --> 33:43.000
in the mind of the buyer.

33:44.000 --> 33:45.000
The buyers do not distinguish

33:46.000 --> 33:47.000
between the sellers

33:47.000 --> 33:49.000
and the sellers themselves.

33:50.000 --> 33:52.000
But when you come to the real tomato market,

33:53.000 --> 33:55.000
you will still walk in rows.

33:56.000 --> 33:57.000
You will see

33:58.000 --> 34:00.000
that here the tomatoes are redder,

34:01.000 --> 34:02.000
and this seller

34:03.000 --> 34:05.000
seems to be less trustworthy.

34:06.000 --> 34:07.000
There is nothing of this

34:08.000 --> 34:10.000
in the conditions of perfect competition.

34:11.000 --> 34:12.000
All sellers

34:13.000 --> 34:14.000
are the same.

34:14.000 --> 34:16.000
And all products are absolutely the same.

34:17.000 --> 34:18.000
There is no difference.

34:19.000 --> 34:21.000
Look at the third sign.

34:22.000 --> 34:24.000
The possibility of free entry

34:25.000 --> 34:26.000
to the market

34:27.000 --> 34:28.000
and leaving it.

34:29.000 --> 34:30.000
This means

34:31.000 --> 34:33.000
that there are no barriers,

34:34.000 --> 34:35.000
financial, administrative,

34:36.000 --> 34:37.000
whatever,

34:38.000 --> 34:39.000
that prevent

34:40.000 --> 34:41.000
the buyer from entering

34:41.000 --> 34:42.000
the market,

34:43.000 --> 34:44.000
new sellers,

34:45.000 --> 34:46.000
or the sellers

34:47.000 --> 34:48.000
from leaving the market.

34:49.000 --> 34:50.000
Let's try

34:51.000 --> 34:52.000
such an example

34:53.000 --> 34:55.000
for the sake of dissection.

34:56.000 --> 34:57.000
Somewhere I read

34:58.000 --> 35:00.000
that our current president,

35:01.000 --> 35:02.000
Vladimir Putin,

35:03.000 --> 35:04.000
in his temporary,

35:05.000 --> 35:07.000
although in tight financial circumstances,

35:08.000 --> 35:09.000
was working as a private importer

35:09.000 --> 35:10.000
on his Zhiguli.

35:11.000 --> 35:12.000
What did this mean?

35:13.000 --> 35:14.000
That he just,

35:15.000 --> 35:16.000
on one beautiful day,

35:17.000 --> 35:18.000
got behind the wheel of his car,

35:19.000 --> 35:21.000
drove to the streets of St. Petersburg,

35:22.000 --> 35:23.000
that is, entered the market

35:24.000 --> 35:25.000
of a private importer.

35:26.000 --> 35:27.000
Some time passed,

35:28.000 --> 35:29.000
Vladimir Putin

35:30.000 --> 35:31.000
found an interesting job

35:32.000 --> 35:33.000
as the President of Russia.

35:34.000 --> 35:35.000
This means only that

35:36.000 --> 35:38.000
he calmly put his Zhiguli

35:39.000 --> 35:40.000
in the garage

35:41.000 --> 35:42.000
and went to work in the Kremlin.

35:43.000 --> 35:44.000
That is, he entered the market

35:45.000 --> 35:46.000
as easily as he left it.

35:47.000 --> 35:49.000
This is a sign of perfect competition.

35:50.000 --> 35:51.000
There are no barriers

35:52.000 --> 35:53.000
for entering and leaving.

35:54.000 --> 35:55.000
The fourth sign

35:56.000 --> 35:57.000
is the perfect knowledge

35:58.000 --> 35:59.000
of the market

36:00.000 --> 36:01.000
by the sellers

36:02.000 --> 36:03.000
and buyers.

36:04.000 --> 36:05.000
Again,

36:06.000 --> 36:07.000
if you come to the real

36:07.000 --> 36:08.000
tomato market,

36:09.000 --> 36:10.000
you will probably

36:11.000 --> 36:12.000
walk in the rows,

36:13.000 --> 36:14.000
look,

36:15.000 --> 36:16.000
maybe there

36:17.000 --> 36:18.000
the tomatoes are better

36:19.000 --> 36:20.000
or a little cheaper.

36:21.000 --> 36:22.000
There is nothing of this

36:23.000 --> 36:24.000
in the condition of perfect competition.

36:25.000 --> 36:26.000
Here all the sellers

36:27.000 --> 36:28.000
and all the buyers

36:29.000 --> 36:30.000
are present.

36:31.000 --> 36:32.000
They seem to have come together

36:33.000 --> 36:34.000
at one point.

36:35.000 --> 36:36.000
All the information about the market

36:37.000 --> 36:38.000
is the same.

36:39.000 --> 36:40.000
It is equally available

36:41.000 --> 36:42.000
to all the sellers

36:43.000 --> 36:44.000
and all the buyers.

36:45.000 --> 36:46.000
But if

36:47.000 --> 36:48.000
we sum up

36:49.000 --> 36:50.000
all that I have said,

36:51.000 --> 36:52.000
then you will probably agree

36:53.000 --> 36:54.000
that perfect competition

36:55.000 --> 36:56.000
is an abstraction.

36:57.000 --> 36:58.000
Such a market

36:59.000 --> 37:00.000
does not exist

37:01.000 --> 37:02.000
in reality.

37:03.000 --> 37:04.000
There are markets

37:05.000 --> 37:06.000
more or less

37:07.000 --> 37:08.000
adhering to this ideal,

37:09.000 --> 37:10.000
but there is no market

37:11.000 --> 37:12.000
in reality of perfect competition.

37:13.000 --> 37:14.000
Then the question is,

37:15.000 --> 37:16.000
if there is no market

37:17.000 --> 37:18.000
of perfect competition,

37:19.000 --> 37:20.000
why should we study it?

37:21.000 --> 37:22.000
The answer is very simple.

37:23.000 --> 37:24.000
For the same reason

37:25.000 --> 37:26.000
that a chemist

37:27.000 --> 37:28.000
studies the properties, for example,

37:29.000 --> 37:30.000
of absolutely pure distilled water,

37:31.000 --> 37:33.000
which does not exist in nature either.

37:34.000 --> 37:35.000
It is simply impossible

37:35.000 --> 37:36.000
to understand

37:37.000 --> 37:38.000
the properties of any impurities

37:39.000 --> 37:40.000
if we do not understand

37:41.000 --> 37:42.000
or study the subject

37:43.000 --> 37:44.000
in a certain ideal state.

37:45.000 --> 37:46.000
I have already mentioned

37:47.000 --> 37:48.000
the first type of market,

37:49.000 --> 37:50.000
the perfect competition.

37:51.000 --> 37:52.000
The second type of market

37:53.000 --> 37:54.000
is called monopoly.

37:56.000 --> 37:57.000
Let us read the definition.

37:58.000 --> 37:59.000
A monopoly is a market structure

38:00.000 --> 38:01.000
in which

38:02.000 --> 38:03.000
the actions of the market

38:03.000 --> 38:04.000
are carried out

38:05.000 --> 38:06.000
by only one company

38:07.000 --> 38:08.000
producing a product

38:09.000 --> 38:10.000
that has no

38:11.000 --> 38:12.000
close substitutes.

38:16.000 --> 38:17.000
Monopolies are found

38:18.000 --> 38:19.000
at the national,

38:20.000 --> 38:21.000
regional,

38:22.000 --> 38:23.000
and most often

38:24.000 --> 38:25.000
at the local level.

38:26.000 --> 38:27.000
But we have national monopolies

38:28.000 --> 38:29.000
in Russia,

38:30.000 --> 38:31.000
in particular

38:31.000 --> 38:32.000
after the reform of the RAOES,

38:33.000 --> 38:34.000
the Federal Network Company

38:35.000 --> 38:36.000
will monopolize

38:37.000 --> 38:38.000
the main lines

38:39.000 --> 38:40.000
of the power generation.

38:41.000 --> 38:42.000
Or, let us say,

38:43.000 --> 38:44.000
in our country

38:45.000 --> 38:46.000
it is a national monopoly.

38:47.000 --> 38:48.000
Or, let us say,

38:49.000 --> 38:50.000
in our city

38:51.000 --> 38:52.000
there is only one company

38:53.000 --> 38:54.000
offering

38:55.000 --> 38:56.000
certain services.

38:57.000 --> 38:58.000
And this is a monopoly.

38:59.000 --> 39:00.000
But still,

39:01.000 --> 39:02.000
the next market structure

39:03.000 --> 39:04.000
is more common.

39:05.000 --> 39:06.000
The oligopoly.

39:07.000 --> 39:08.000
What is it?

39:09.000 --> 39:10.000
Let us look at the definition.

39:11.000 --> 39:12.000
The oligopoly

39:13.000 --> 39:14.000
is a market structure

39:15.000 --> 39:16.000
characterized

39:17.000 --> 39:18.000
by a small number

39:19.000 --> 39:20.000
of active firms.

39:21.000 --> 39:22.000
The oligopoly

39:23.000 --> 39:24.000
is a market structure

39:25.000 --> 39:26.000
characterized by a small number

39:26.000 --> 39:27.000
of active firms.

39:31.000 --> 39:33.000
Here are some examples of the oligopoly.

39:34.000 --> 39:35.000
