01:09:19.000 --> 01:09:20.000
are increased

01:09:21.000 --> 01:09:22.000
by one unit.

01:09:23.000 --> 01:09:24.000
Accordingly,

01:09:25.000 --> 01:09:26.000
the marginal income

01:09:27.000 --> 01:09:28.000
is the additional income

01:09:29.000 --> 01:09:30.000
that the company gets

01:09:31.000 --> 01:09:32.000
when the additional units

01:09:33.000 --> 01:09:34.000
of the product

01:09:35.000 --> 01:09:36.000
are produced and sold.

01:09:37.000 --> 01:09:38.000
Take a look.

01:09:39.000 --> 01:09:40.000
The simplest example

01:09:41.000 --> 01:09:42.000
of the calculation

01:09:43.000 --> 01:09:44.000
of the marginal income

01:09:45.000 --> 01:09:46.000
is shown on the slide.

01:09:47.000 --> 01:09:48.000
Yes,

01:09:49.000 --> 01:09:50.000
just a small remark.

01:09:51.000 --> 01:09:52.000
While we are talking

01:09:53.000 --> 01:09:55.000
about a completely competitive company,

01:09:57.000 --> 01:09:58.000
its marginal income

01:09:59.000 --> 01:10:01.000
is equal to the price of the product.

01:10:03.000 --> 01:10:04.000
In fact,

01:10:05.000 --> 01:10:06.000
a completely competitive company

01:10:07.000 --> 01:10:08.000
sells any amount

01:10:09.000 --> 01:10:10.000
of its product

01:10:10.000 --> 01:10:11.000
at the market price.

01:10:14.000 --> 01:10:16.000
The price for a completely competitive company

01:10:17.000 --> 01:10:18.000
is the given price.

01:10:21.000 --> 01:10:22.000
And if this is true,

01:10:24.000 --> 01:10:25.000
then each additional unit

01:10:26.000 --> 01:10:27.000
of the product

01:10:28.000 --> 01:10:29.000
brings the company

01:10:30.000 --> 01:10:31.000
additional revenue,

01:10:33.000 --> 01:10:34.000
additional income

01:10:35.000 --> 01:10:36.000
equal to this price.

01:10:40.000 --> 01:10:41.000
If, for example,

01:10:42.000 --> 01:10:43.000
the company sells

01:10:44.000 --> 01:10:46.000
a product at the price of 10 rubles,

01:10:47.000 --> 01:10:48.000
each additional unit

01:10:49.000 --> 01:10:50.000
of the product

01:10:51.000 --> 01:10:52.000
will increase

01:10:53.000 --> 01:10:54.000
the company's revenue

01:10:55.000 --> 01:10:56.000
by 10 rubles.

01:10:57.000 --> 01:10:58.000
Thus, the company's marginal income

01:10:59.000 --> 01:11:00.000
is equal to the price

01:11:01.000 --> 01:11:02.000
of the product

01:11:03.000 --> 01:11:04.000
it sells.

01:11:06.000 --> 01:11:07.000
And now,

01:11:07.000 --> 01:11:08.000
please look at the table

01:11:09.000 --> 01:11:10.000
on the slide.

01:11:11.000 --> 01:11:12.000
You see,

01:11:13.000 --> 01:11:14.000
the company's output changes

01:11:15.000 --> 01:11:16.000
in the first column.

01:11:17.000 --> 01:11:18.000
I change it here

01:11:19.000 --> 01:11:20.000
from 0 to 5.

01:11:21.000 --> 01:11:22.000
The price, as we have already said,

01:11:23.000 --> 01:11:24.000
for a completely competitive company

01:11:25.000 --> 01:11:26.000
is constant,

01:11:27.000 --> 01:11:28.000
let's say 10 rubles.

01:11:29.000 --> 01:11:30.000
By multiplying the price

01:11:31.000 --> 01:11:32.000
by the volume of sales,

01:11:33.000 --> 01:11:34.000
I get

01:11:34.000 --> 01:11:35.000
the company's revenue.

01:11:36.000 --> 01:11:37.000
It changes

01:11:38.000 --> 01:11:39.000
with the change in the output.

01:11:40.000 --> 01:11:41.000
And you see,

01:11:42.000 --> 01:11:43.000
it changes linearly

01:11:44.000 --> 01:11:45.000
0, 10, 20, 30, 40, 50,

01:11:46.000 --> 01:11:47.000
as we have just said.

01:11:50.000 --> 01:11:51.000
What is the marginal income equal to?

01:11:52.000 --> 01:11:53.000
Let's calculate.

01:11:54.000 --> 01:11:55.000
What is the marginal income?

01:11:56.000 --> 01:11:57.000
It is the delta of the revenue,

01:11:58.000 --> 01:11:59.000
that is, the return on the revenue

01:12:00.000 --> 01:12:01.000
divided by the return on the revenue.

01:12:01.000 --> 01:12:02.000
The return on the revenue

01:12:03.000 --> 01:12:04.000
is always 1,

01:12:05.000 --> 01:12:06.000
and the return on the revenue

01:12:07.000 --> 01:12:08.000
is always 10.

01:12:09.000 --> 01:12:10.000
That is,

01:12:11.000 --> 01:12:12.000
the marginal income

01:12:13.000 --> 01:12:14.000
is equal to

01:12:15.000 --> 01:12:16.000
the price of the product

01:12:17.000 --> 01:12:18.000
for a completely competitive company.

01:12:19.000 --> 01:12:20.000
I repeat,

01:12:21.000 --> 01:12:22.000
for a monopoly.

01:12:23.000 --> 01:12:24.000
We will talk about it later.

01:12:25.000 --> 01:12:26.000
Let's move on

01:12:27.000 --> 01:12:28.000
to the third question.

01:12:28.000 --> 01:12:29.000
The balance

01:12:30.000 --> 01:12:31.000
of a completely competitive company.

01:12:32.000 --> 01:12:33.000
Here we assume

01:12:34.000 --> 01:12:35.000
that the company

01:12:36.000 --> 01:12:37.000
strives

01:12:38.000 --> 01:12:39.000
to maximize

01:12:40.000 --> 01:12:41.000
its profit.

01:12:42.000 --> 01:12:43.000
What is a profit?

01:12:44.000 --> 01:12:45.000
It is very simple.

01:12:46.000 --> 01:12:47.000
Look at the slide.

01:12:48.000 --> 01:12:49.000
A profit

01:12:50.000 --> 01:12:51.000
is the difference

01:12:52.000 --> 01:12:53.000
between the company's revenue

01:12:54.000 --> 01:12:55.000
and its total profit.

01:12:55.000 --> 01:12:56.000
That is,

01:12:57.000 --> 01:12:58.000
the profit is equal to

01:12:59.000 --> 01:13:00.000
the revenue

01:13:01.000 --> 01:13:02.000
minus the total

01:13:03.000 --> 01:13:04.000
cost.

01:13:05.000 --> 01:13:06.000
I repeat,

01:13:07.000 --> 01:13:08.000
the company wants

01:13:09.000 --> 01:13:10.000
to maximize

01:13:11.000 --> 01:13:12.000
this difference,

01:13:13.000 --> 01:13:14.000
that is, the profit.

01:13:15.000 --> 01:13:16.000
Theoretically,

01:13:17.000 --> 01:13:18.000
the problem is solved very simply.

01:13:19.000 --> 01:13:20.000
The company's profit

01:13:21.000 --> 01:13:22.000
is maximized

01:13:23.000 --> 01:13:24.000
by the total

01:13:25.000 --> 01:13:26.000
cost.

01:13:27.000 --> 01:13:28.000
How to explain it?

01:13:29.000 --> 01:13:30.000
Look.

01:13:31.000 --> 01:13:32.000
My company

01:13:33.000 --> 01:13:34.000
is engaged

01:13:35.000 --> 01:13:36.000
in the production

01:13:37.000 --> 01:13:38.000
of a product

01:13:39.000 --> 01:13:40.000
or a service.

01:13:41.000 --> 01:13:42.000
Let's say

01:13:43.000 --> 01:13:44.000
I increase

01:13:45.000 --> 01:13:46.000
the total

01:13:47.000 --> 01:13:48.000
cost

01:13:49.000 --> 01:13:50.000
by a fraction.

01:13:51.000 --> 01:13:52.000
I increase

01:13:53.000 --> 01:13:54.000
the total

01:13:55.000 --> 01:13:56.000
cost

01:13:57.000 --> 01:13:58.000
by one more fraction.

01:14:00.000 --> 01:14:01.000
I get

01:14:02.000 --> 01:14:03.000
additional income

01:14:04.000 --> 01:14:05.000
or in our terms

01:14:06.000 --> 01:14:07.000
the maximum income.

01:14:08.000 --> 01:14:09.000
That's good.

01:14:10.000 --> 01:14:11.000
But at the same time

01:14:12.000 --> 01:14:13.000
I will have to bear

01:14:14.000 --> 01:14:15.000
additional costs.

01:14:16.000 --> 01:14:17.000
That's bad.

01:14:18.000 --> 01:14:19.000
Nevertheless,

01:14:20.000 --> 01:14:21.000
if the additional income,

01:14:22.000 --> 01:14:23.000
that is, the maximum income,

01:14:23.000 --> 01:14:24.000
is higher than the additional costs,

01:14:25.000 --> 01:14:26.000
that is, the maximum costs,

01:14:27.000 --> 01:14:28.000
then the additional

01:14:29.000 --> 01:14:30.000
unit of the production

01:14:31.000 --> 01:14:32.000
will increase

01:14:33.000 --> 01:14:34.000
the profit

01:14:35.000 --> 01:14:36.000
of my company.

01:14:37.000 --> 01:14:38.000
And while

01:14:39.000 --> 01:14:40.000
the maximum income

01:14:41.000 --> 01:14:42.000
exceeds the maximum costs,

01:14:43.000 --> 01:14:44.000
the increase

01:14:45.000 --> 01:14:46.000
of the production

01:14:47.000 --> 01:14:48.000
leads to the increase

01:14:49.000 --> 01:14:50.000
of the profit.

01:14:50.000 --> 01:14:51.000
The total profit

01:14:52.000 --> 01:14:53.000
of the company

01:14:54.000 --> 01:14:55.000
is increased

01:14:56.000 --> 01:14:57.000
by all units of production.

01:14:59.000 --> 01:15:00.000
So,

01:15:01.000 --> 01:15:02.000
as soon as the maximum income

01:15:03.000 --> 01:15:04.000
is equal to the maximum costs,

01:15:05.000 --> 01:15:06.000
the additional unit

01:15:07.000 --> 01:15:08.000
of production

01:15:09.000 --> 01:15:10.000
stops increasing

01:15:11.000 --> 01:15:12.000
the total profit

01:15:13.000 --> 01:15:14.000
of the company.

01:15:15.000 --> 01:15:16.000
And the total profit

01:15:17.000 --> 01:15:18.000
has reached

01:15:18.000 --> 01:15:19.000
the maximum.

01:15:20.000 --> 01:15:21.000
So,

01:15:22.000 --> 01:15:23.000
the profit of a completely

01:15:24.000 --> 01:15:25.000
competitive company

01:15:26.000 --> 01:15:27.000
at such a volume of production

01:15:28.000 --> 01:15:29.000
is equal to

01:15:30.000 --> 01:15:31.000
its maximum costs.

01:15:32.000 --> 01:15:33.000
Let's,

01:15:34.000 --> 01:15:35.000
to make it clearer,

01:15:36.000 --> 01:15:37.000
look at

01:15:38.000 --> 01:15:39.000
a conditional numerical example.

01:15:40.000 --> 01:15:41.000
Let's say,

01:15:42.000 --> 01:15:43.000
we have a company

01:15:44.000 --> 01:15:45.000
that is producing

01:15:45.000 --> 01:15:46.000
a certain amount of goods.

01:15:47.000 --> 01:15:48.000
Let's look at

01:15:49.000 --> 01:15:50.000
a conditional numerical example.

01:15:51.000 --> 01:15:52.000
Here,

01:15:53.000 --> 01:15:54.000
please,

01:15:55.000 --> 01:15:56.000
look at the table.

01:15:57.000 --> 01:15:58.000
In the first column,

01:15:59.000 --> 01:16:00.000
there are changes in production

01:16:01.000 --> 01:16:02.000
from 0 to 10.

01:16:03.000 --> 01:16:04.000
In the second column,

01:16:05.000 --> 01:16:06.000
there are constant costs.

01:16:07.000 --> 01:16:08.000
Well, the constant costs

01:16:09.000 --> 01:16:10.000
do not change

01:16:11.000 --> 01:16:12.000
by definition,

01:16:13.000 --> 01:16:14.000
they do not depend on production.

01:16:15.000 --> 01:16:16.000
The variable costs

01:16:17.000 --> 01:16:18.000
are shown

01:16:19.000 --> 01:16:20.000
as variable costs

01:16:21.000 --> 01:16:22.000
change with the change in production.

01:16:24.000 --> 01:16:25.000
These values

01:16:26.000 --> 01:16:27.000
are given initially.

01:16:28.000 --> 01:16:29.000
All other values,

01:16:30.000 --> 01:16:31.000
at least in terms of costs,

01:16:32.000 --> 01:16:33.000
are calculated.

01:16:35.000 --> 01:16:36.000
Knowing the constant

01:16:37.000 --> 01:16:38.000
and variable costs,

01:16:39.000 --> 01:16:40.000
we can calculate

01:16:41.000 --> 01:16:42.000
the total costs.

01:16:43.000 --> 01:16:44.000
We can calculate

01:16:45.000 --> 01:16:46.000
the average constant costs,

01:16:47.000 --> 01:16:48.000
the average variable costs,

01:16:49.000 --> 01:16:50.000
and the average total costs.

01:16:52.000 --> 01:16:53.000
I hope you remember the formulas.

01:16:55.000 --> 01:16:56.000
And finally,

01:16:57.000 --> 01:16:58.000
in the next column,

01:16:59.000 --> 01:17:00.000
we have

01:17:01.000 --> 01:17:02.000
the maximum costs.

01:17:03.000 --> 01:17:04.000
How do we get

01:17:05.000 --> 01:17:06.000
the maximum costs?

01:17:07.000 --> 01:17:08.000
Look again.

01:17:09.000 --> 01:17:10.000
I remind you,

01:17:11.000 --> 01:17:12.000
the maximum costs

01:17:13.000 --> 01:17:14.000
are the addition

01:17:15.000 --> 01:17:16.000
of the total costs

01:17:17.000 --> 01:17:18.000
when the output

01:17:19.000 --> 01:17:20.000
is 1.

01:17:21.000 --> 01:17:22.000
The output always increases

01:17:23.000 --> 01:17:24.000
by 1.

01:17:25.000 --> 01:17:26.000
I divide the addition

01:17:27.000 --> 01:17:28.000
of the total costs

01:17:29.000 --> 01:17:30.000
by 1 when the output is 1.

01:17:31.000 --> 01:17:32.000
So,

01:17:33.000 --> 01:17:34.000
when the output

01:17:35.000 --> 01:17:36.000
goes from 0 to 1,

01:17:37.000 --> 01:17:38.000
the total costs

01:17:39.000 --> 01:17:40.000
increase by 32 rubles.

01:17:42.000 --> 01:17:43.000
These are the maximum costs.

01:17:43.000 --> 01:17:44.000
These are the additional costs

01:17:45.000 --> 01:17:46.000
that we will have to bear

01:17:47.000 --> 01:17:48.000
if we want to increase

01:17:49.000 --> 01:17:50.000
the output

01:17:51.000 --> 01:17:52.000
from 0 to 1.

01:17:54.000 --> 01:17:55.000
Then,

01:17:56.000 --> 01:17:57.000
we increase the output

01:17:58.000 --> 01:17:59.000
by 1,

01:18:00.000 --> 01:18:01.000
from 1 to 2.

01:18:02.000 --> 01:18:03.000
How much do the total costs increase?

01:18:05.000 --> 01:18:06.000
By 20 units.

01:18:07.000 --> 01:18:08.000
These are the maximum costs

01:18:09.000 --> 01:18:10.000
when the output

01:18:11.000 --> 01:18:12.000
goes from 1 to 2.

01:18:13.000 --> 01:18:14.000
And so on.

01:18:15.000 --> 01:18:16.000
Please note

01:18:17.000 --> 01:18:18.000
that the maximum costs

01:18:19.000 --> 01:18:20.000
decrease at first,

01:18:23.000 --> 01:18:25.000
then reach the minimum.

01:18:26.000 --> 01:18:27.000
Do you see the minimum?

01:18:28.000 --> 01:18:29.000
At the output of 4 units,

01:18:30.000 --> 01:18:31.000
the maximum costs

01:18:32.000 --> 01:18:33.000
become minimal.

01:18:35.000 --> 01:18:36.000
And then the maximum costs

01:18:37.000 --> 01:18:38.000
begin to increase.

01:18:40.000 --> 01:18:41.000
That is, we deal

01:18:41.000 --> 01:18:42.000
with the classic

01:18:43.000 --> 01:18:44.000
U-shaped curve

01:18:45.000 --> 01:18:46.000
of the maximum costs

01:18:47.000 --> 01:18:48.000
that we have already discussed

01:18:49.000 --> 01:18:50.000
in the previous topic.

01:18:51.000 --> 01:18:52.000
The next column

01:18:54.000 --> 01:18:55.000
is the price.

01:18:57.000 --> 01:18:58.000
But if the company

01:18:59.000 --> 01:19:00.000
is completely competitive,

01:19:01.000 --> 01:19:02.000
then, as I have said many times,

01:19:03.000 --> 01:19:04.000
the maximum income

01:19:05.000 --> 01:19:06.000
of such a company

01:19:07.000 --> 01:19:08.000
is always equal to the price

01:19:09.000 --> 01:19:10.000
of the product

01:19:12.000 --> 01:19:13.000
I have set the price,

01:19:14.000 --> 01:19:15.000
the price is 30,

01:19:16.000 --> 01:19:17.000
the maximum income

01:19:18.000 --> 01:19:19.000
of a completely competitive company

01:19:20.000 --> 01:19:21.000
is always constant

01:19:22.000 --> 01:19:23.000
and equal to the price.

01:19:24.000 --> 01:19:25.000
Now look carefully

01:19:26.000 --> 01:19:27.000
at the table.

01:19:30.000 --> 01:19:31.000
We increase

01:19:32.000 --> 01:19:33.000
the output all the time.

01:19:35.000 --> 01:19:36.000
And so,

01:19:37.000 --> 01:19:38.000
starting

01:19:38.000 --> 01:19:39.000
from 2 units of the output,

01:19:40.000 --> 01:19:41.000
the maximum income

01:19:42.000 --> 01:19:43.000
or price

01:19:44.000 --> 01:19:45.000
exceeds the maximum costs.

01:19:46.000 --> 01:19:47.000
For example,

01:19:48.000 --> 01:19:49.000
at the output of 3 units

01:19:50.000 --> 01:19:51.000
the maximum income

01:19:52.000 --> 01:19:53.000
is equal to

01:19:55.000 --> 01:19:56.000
30,

01:19:57.000 --> 01:19:58.000
and the maximum costs

01:19:59.000 --> 01:20:00.000
are equal to

01:20:01.000 --> 01:20:02.000
12.

01:20:03.000 --> 01:20:04.000
What does this mean?

01:20:06.000 --> 01:20:07.000
That if we release

01:20:08.000 --> 01:20:09.000
the third unit of the product,

01:20:10.000 --> 01:20:11.000
our profit

01:20:12.000 --> 01:20:13.000
will increase.

01:20:14.000 --> 01:20:15.000
In fact,

01:20:16.000 --> 01:20:17.000
look at the last column.

01:20:20.000 --> 01:20:21.000
The profit in this zone

01:20:22.000 --> 01:20:23.000
is still negative,

01:20:24.000 --> 01:20:25.000
but

01:20:26.000 --> 01:20:27.000
when the output is increased,

01:20:28.000 --> 01:20:29.000
the negative profit

01:20:30.000 --> 01:20:31.000
begins to decrease.

01:20:34.000 --> 01:20:35.000
That is, the profit increases.

01:20:39.000 --> 01:20:40.000
And look,

01:20:41.000 --> 01:20:42.000
at the output of 5 units,

01:20:47.000 --> 01:20:48.000
we already get

01:20:49.000 --> 01:20:50.000
a positive profit.

01:20:51.000 --> 01:20:52.000
It is equal to 8.

01:20:54.000 --> 01:20:55.000
Nevertheless,

01:20:56.000 --> 01:20:57.000
at this output

01:20:58.000 --> 01:20:59.000
we will not stop.

01:21:00.000 --> 01:21:01.000
Why?

01:21:02.000 --> 01:21:03.000
Because if we release

01:21:04.000 --> 01:21:05.000
the sixth unit of the product,

01:21:06.000 --> 01:21:07.000
the maximum income is equal to

01:21:08.000 --> 01:21:09.000
30,

01:21:10.000 --> 01:21:11.000
and the maximum costs

01:21:12.000 --> 01:21:13.000
are equal to 18.

01:21:14.000 --> 01:21:15.000
That is, the sixth unit of the product

01:21:17.000 --> 01:21:18.000
will require 18 rubles

01:21:19.000 --> 01:21:20.000
of additional costs,

01:21:21.000 --> 01:21:22.000
but will bring 30 rubles

01:21:23.000 --> 01:21:24.000
of additional income.

01:21:27.000 --> 01:21:28.000
So,

01:21:32.000 --> 01:21:33.000
how much will the profit increase?

01:21:35.000 --> 01:21:36.000
By 12 rubles.

01:21:36.000 --> 01:21:37.000
And in fact,

01:21:38.000 --> 01:21:39.000
at the output of 5 units

01:21:40.000 --> 01:21:41.000
the profit was 8,

01:21:42.000 --> 01:21:43.000
and at the output of 6 units

01:21:44.000 --> 01:21:45.000
it is already equal to 20.

